Gregorovic, also known as The Faceless One, is the general of Sliske's army in the Heart of Gielinor. Level 80 Prayer is required to face him.

Obtaining all unique drops will unlock the title, [Name] the Faceless One.

Sliske's Endgame[edit | edit source]

This article or section is incomplete and could do with improvement.
Reason: Sliske's Endgame mechanics and stats
You can discuss this issue on the talk page or edit this page to improve it.

When fought in Sliske's Endgame, Gregorovic uses a different set of attacks, and unlike the encounter in the Heart of Gielinor, his attacks do not poison.

  • Healing spirit: Gregorovic may occasionally call for a healing spirit which will dart towards him; if it touches him, it will heal him for 10,000 life points. If Gregorovic was not defeated first, the spirit will heal 20,000 life points instead.
  • Knife throw: If Gregorovic was not defeated first, he can perform his knife throw attack (where he tosses his glaives in the air), acting the same as the one he performs in the Heart of Gielinor.
  • Clones: If Gregorovic is the last enemy standing, he can summon shadows which are the same as those encountered in the Heart of Gielinor.

History[edit | edit source]

Early history[edit | edit source]

The following takes place during Tales of the God Wars (miniquest).

Gregorovic was a fatally ill human of the Fourth Age, who was desperate to avoid death. In the hope of prolonging his life, he captured some Cywir elves and employed torturous experiments in order to find out the secret of their long lifespan. His work was unsuccessful, and he believed that some sort of "elven magic" beyond his comprehension was responsible; his suspicions were true, but the elves were not responsible for this; Seren was the one who had done so. One of these elves managed to escape, informing their lord of the atrocities he committed, prompting him and his clan who followed him to Gielinor to search for him to avenge their fallen kin.

When this failed, he sought out the Mahjarrat Sliske at the Barrows, and offered him his soul in return for eternal life. Sliske accepted his offer, but questioned whether Gregorovic had thought his proposal through. Sliske then summoned an abyssal demon called Erasinus, who proceeded to eat Gregorovic's body and soul, and subsequently came to believe himself to be Gregorovic, taking a monstrous new form resembling a macabre jester. Gregorovic was initially horrified and told Sliske that he had made him a monster, but Sliske told him that he had already been one. Sliske then instructed him on how to maintain this form, and upon learning that he could become even stronger and could continue adding to his lifespan, swore fealty to the Mahjarrat.

Gregorovic was not called for by Sliske for the entire duration of both the Fourth and Fifth Ages, despite having been turned into a valuable asset. He simply wandered around Gielinor for thousands of years, consuming all in his path. One of these victims was an Avernic demon. The demon's sisters, Nymora and Avaryss (now known as the Twin Furies) swore vengeance against Gregorovic, although he was easily able to elude them.

When the Heart was discovered, Gregorovic was called upon by Sliske to claim the anima in his name. Helwyr and the Twin Furies had also arrived to claim it for their respective gods, and both parties swore revenge on him for the deaths he had caused. In the ensuing battle for control of the Heart, Gregorovic's forces consist of necromancers and the undead.

Sliske's Endgame[edit | edit source]

The following takes place during Sliske's Endgame.

Gregorovic makes an appearance in Sliske's Endgame, where he is summoned by Sliske to kill the World Guardian alongside an undead Nomad and Linza the Disgraced, using many of the same abilities as he does in the Heart. Though he was killed by the World Guardian, he was revived and despite the loss of his master, continued to lead his forces in the Heart.

Insanity[edit | edit source]

The following takes place during Azzanadra's Quest.

Gregorovic's army was eventually defeated as the necromancers withdrew and his undead minions were destroyed with Sliske's death. When the World Guardian, Azzanadra and Ariane entered the Heart to access the Elder Halls, they were stopped by Helwyr and his warriors. In part due to Sliske transferring his essence to the World Guardian before his demise, Gregorovic was drawn to the World Guardian. Seeing Helwyr, he then taunted him about his son's demise by his hands, prompting the enraged elf to chase after him with his forces.

Peace[edit | edit source]

The following takes place during Twilight of the Gods.

Gregorovic eventually made his way to a post-battle Senntisten where he relished in consuming the flesh of the White Knights, while his true identity as Erasinus re-emerged on returning to his former home. He also met Naressa during this time, and helped her and the White Knights transport the bodies of the deceased out of the city. The World Guardian, who had been sent to investigate, discovered Gregorovic and learned from their voices that Gregorovic was a demon, and that his Erasinus and Gregorovic personas were mentally clashing with each other for supremacy. The World Guardian ordered Gregorovic to stand down and not cause any havoc, who willingly obeyed the alternate voices.

Upon meeting with several Infernal demons (in actuality Aughra Dragonkin inhabiting the bodies of Avernic demons), the World Guardian learned some of their Chthonian servants were suffering from the same condition as Erasinus, and they proceeded to make a cure. They tested it on Erasinus and Senecianus, killing the Gregorovic persona for good, and reverting Erasinus's form back to that of an abyssal demon.

Trivia[edit | edit source]

  • Gregorovic's design was partly inspired by Voldo from the video game series Soulcalibur.[2]
  • In the concept art Gregorovic is referred to as "the Mannequin".
  • The name "Gregorovic" may be a reference to "Gregorovitch", a character from Harry Potter.
  • After killing Gregorovic, the Adventurer's Log will say: "I killed the blade wielding terror, Gregorovic." Killing more than one Gregorovic results in the Adventurer's Log saying: "I killed # Gregorovics, all blade wielding terrors."
  • Gregorovic's combat level randomly changes anywhere from 1-1,000 during the course of the fight; this does not seem to affect his actual strength in any way, but it does make him susceptible to dominion mines if his combat level is 138 or lower.
  • As of 19 December 2016, Gregorovic is the highest-levelled quest boss at level 1,000, when he fights alongside Nomad (the previous titleholder) and Linza the Disgraced at the end of Sliske's Endgame.
  • In the lobby area in an instance, if no one enters the arena, Gregorovic will repeatedly say "I'm so lonely." until someone enters.
  • Gregorovic's weapon, the Shadow Glaive, is based on the weapon from the British film Krull.
  • During the fight with Gregorovic, Akrisae the Doomed with one million life points may rarely appear and start attacking the player. The conditions required for this to happen are unknown.
  • As of 1 February 2018, the highest kill count for this boss was 51,937 kills for normal mode and 1,490 for hard mode.[3]
    • This had increased to 52,183 for normal mode and 1,880 for hard mode by 13 December 2018. At the time this data was collected, only two Hardcore ironman accounts have logged at least one kill in hard mode.[4]
  • Despite being a demon in disguise, he drops bones instead of demonic ashes. However, he was released before his true identity was revealed.
